    }, "While at GCI/QSI, the spiritu santus nature of some of my female Christian classmates used to put me off. They were never smiling, so I did not want anything to do with them. In June, just before my UI admission, I was cleaning my parents\u2019 living room when I saw an old and worn book called the Lydia book of the Baptist. Flipping through to see if it was worth saving, I ended up reading the whole book, full of salvation message. I felt so broken and convinced. I read the sinners prayers and there gave my life to Christ. That was the beginning of my Christian Journey. I longed for more books like this that shows your dependency and sufficiency only in Christ. With the help of the Daily Bread and the Gideon\u2019s Bible with the Anglican hymns, I tried to fill some of the vacuum. This hunger and thirst followed me to UI. The decision of which fellowship to settle down with \u2013 IVCU or SCM \u2013 was made easy because the spiritu santus were in IVCU. Also, my class schedule favored the Thursday fellowship. So I settled myself in SCM to meet some familiar faces and welcoming hands. Of course we were a smaller group, but you could almost physically touch LOVE. They lived and carried the love of God in their eyes, their voices and their choices. I resolved to love and shape my life like this. The likes of my Bros. Kolapo, Tenu Adeosun, Babatunde Okikiolu, Sis Bola Sofela were my classmates and and also in SCM. We were all pampered and loved by the older ones. The love was also very genuine and no ulterior motives. People would choose to visit me on their birthdays. And you better be prepared to encourage them with some scriptures. Bro Biodun Adeniyi in Transport spoilt me, and when Bruuche my cousin took over, you can imagine what the squad of him and Bro Kenny Akindemowo did for me & Idia Hall Sisters. Bro Dave Fadugba was like a bigger brother I never had. Bro Tosin Odunsi was one of those jimjim brothers you see like Father Christmas especially when he moved to UCH. Bro Charles with his tenses, grammar and accents was my president when I joined the fellowship and I think sis Toyin Adesokan was the Vice. Strong and don\u2019t mess with her Her bible study class will make you want to read the whole bible. Bro Moses, our bible study sec was an encyclopedia of various editions of the Bible. He was always in his characteristics short sleeve shirt. Bro Bro Motunrayo was my follow up brother and you better be paying attention when he visit because he is very soft spoken. Those visit ensures that whatever you had for quiet time be ruminated upon because you can easily fall back to them during any follow up visit. Bro Biodun Olojo, was one President that checked upon us whenever we are having joint practice with IVCU choir during Easter/Festive season. Bro Victor Ola Akande and Bro Ebenezer babatope, I remember we decided to join grass root politics out when souls were perishing, it was simply joblessness. School was on strike but we learnt some core political moves. I remember I will write to encourage the new fellowship president during their swearing in. That always makes me pray for them too. I recall my days with chapel Sunday school held in the basement and on Palm Sunday we will have the best behave students ride the donkey to around Abadina with the rest of the students walking behind with their palm leaves sing Hossanah . The chapel days reminds me of the ushers most of them were SCMers in the usher\u2019s robe and the likes of sis Nike and sister Iyeseun, in chapel choir as well as the pride I used to have with bro Niran Obasa at the piano, scm served with pride through bro Lekan Orenuga, sis Funmi Olukoju, sis Bola  Olusesi, my sis Omolade Adebayo. SCMers were very active in chapel. and friends like Bro Olumide Folalu, Bro Mike Ogundimbola, Bro Olumide Ajibawo, were as close as a glove. Free and relaxed with SCMers, I never needed to act in SCM. Choir was such a closely knit family, and we were special. The EDV with Bros Kenny Olatoye, Ayoola Aladeojebi, Niran Obasa \u2013 I\u2019m going to get myself into trouble now because everyone in Choir was special to me. Oh! I can\u2019t forget Sis Oyoma; classmate, choir and same hall. Sis Evelyn roommate \u2013 more than a sister. My All the \u201CRere ma ni o\u201D popular choir song team. I remember I used to ride with Sister Iyabo Obasanjo in her Volkswagen Beetle back to the hall before I joined the exco. I remember how we shared everything. All exco had to accommodate as many sisters as your roommate will allow. As the former treasurer, the new treasurer had no accommodation so, sis Motunde has to be with me. Unfortunately my sister too got admission and no accommodation. Making 3 of us, then bro Lekan Orenuga came for a 2mins visit and brought a jambito from \u201CIlu oke\u201D with him and as he was leaving he said sister Ronke, take care of her o. I ran after him what do you mean my roommate has her squatters and we are 3 already and it was a small D block in Queens hall. He stepped back and said, if she were to be a brother I won\u2019t come here. I\u2019m entrusting her into your care. When my sister came back to see that I have another person to share my corner with, she called my Daddy that she needs her own accommodation promptly because there was no end to how many people I will keep accommodating. But I bless God for that opportunity because my jambito of 1992 is a full professor today and assisted me in obtaining admissions for some of our kids on this platform. She is Prof.Simbo Apata nee Arowojolu.", /*#__PURE__*/React.createElement("br", {
