        fileName: _jsxFileName,
        lineNumber: 106,
        columnNumber: 19
      }
    }), "I recall our exco meeting that some people claim I made them wait till after midnight in Chapel. For what? I wonder! When grammatical grenades are thrown about incessantly!! In one statement Bro Debo would have coined three new words softly spoken and juxtaposed, leaving half of us in wonderment of what he meant.", /*#__PURE__*/React.createElement("br", {
      __self: this,
      __source: {
        fileName: _jsxFileName,
        lineNumber: 107,
        columnNumber: 19
      }
    }), "I enjoyed love like no one else, SCM was home within a home for me. Another event I remember was the eve of my 21st birthday. I was just getting ready to go home, had been ill since morning and Sister Bola Olusesi asked me to come stay in her room and she would take me home in the evening. Suddenly I became nauseous and I vomited. Sister Bola asked me to go and clean my face first with water, and as I turned to do that she locked the door so that I didn\u2019t have access to the room and she cleansed the emesis. If she didn\u2019t I would have continued the act because I could not see it and not start another round. But I\u2019ve been eternally grateful to that little saint and big but humble Sister Bola that showed me that when you love someone, you can clean up after them. She did not mind my dirtying her room. She took care of me and took care of the job. Thank you Sis Bola, you may not know how much you mean to me but you mean the world to me.", /*#__PURE__*/React.createElement("br", {
      __self: this,
      __source: {
        fileName: _jsxFileName,
        lineNumber: 108,
        columnNumber: 19
      }
    }), "I have to stop before I get myself into trouble because I have good history with almost everybody. Let\u2019s wrap it up with kudos to the likes of Sisters Iyabo Duduyemi, Foluke Awotoye, Lade Ayeni, etc., who taught me how to make \u201Cmoimoi elewe\u201D whenever we had Awareness. Those fellowships that we moved around one another\u2019s house during those ASUU strikes; those lovely brethren visits I received at home \u2013 I cannot forget.", /*#__PURE__*/React.createElement("br", {
      __self: this,
      __source: {
        fileName: _jsxFileName,
        lineNumber: 109,
        columnNumber: 19
      }
    }), "I recall when SCM National was 50 and I was to be one of the ushers for the WSCF delegates but unfortunately their flight was delayed so they came late. I kept asking that I had to go home but the venue we used did not have commercial rides and it was on outskirts of the town at that time, so I had to wait for the National President to take me and others after he must have attended to the arriving delegates from outside the country. By the time he was ready, I was crying because I knew you don\u2019t disobey my mum. You just don\u2019t come home in the dark. It was not the time of cell phones. She would have waited endlessly at the shop and gone home out of fear, about 10-11pm. The way I was so afraid made him not drop others whose houses were on the way but he rushed to drop me home. We got home and fearfully I approached our gate. The whole street was dark (no light) but the generator was on so I knew my mum had not slept. I shook the gate and when my mum answered she told me to go back to where I was coming from. I told her it was a fellowship program but all my explanations fell on deaf ears. Mr Adegbolagun then spoke up appealing to her and she was furious asking him if he had children and if his daughters come home at 10pm after leaving the house since 8am. She would not open the gate and everyone in the car asked me to follow them back but I stayed, and a while after they left, she came to open the gate. Since then, I haven\u2019t seen my poor National President to apologize for the insult.", /*#__PURE__*/React.createElement("br", {
      __self: this,
      __source: {
        fileName: _jsxFileName,
        lineNumber: 109,
        columnNumber: 1531
      }
    }), "I had the good, the bad and the ugly, in UI. What built resilience in me and prepared me like no other for the larger world was that I had extra years in UI, not one semester, not 2 semesters, not 3 semesters but 4 semesters because the class that I had problem with was a second semester class which I didn\u2019t know I had problems with until the end of my 3rd year. This experience rendered my graduating grade to a pass. This gave me the experience and platform for a conscious and independent spiritual growth. I had the proverbial Israelite journey in life and I was made stronger for it. Ran a postgraduate course in OSU, became a Chartered Accountant, became CISA certified and came back for a Masters program in UI in 2004 before leaving the country and finding greater fulfillment in the medical field.", /*#__PURE__*/React.createElement("br", {
